WEBVTT

00:00.709 --> 00:02.920
[♪♪♪]

00:05.923 --> 00:08.801
ELIZABETH:
Jack and I had
the most glorious honeymoon

00:08.801 --> 00:10.552
on the way to Fort Clay.

00:10.552 --> 00:12.888
We had picnics by Otsego Lake,

00:12.888 --> 00:15.432
and romantic dinners
at quaint restaurants.

00:16.350 --> 00:18.978
I cherished every moment.

00:21.396 --> 00:23.816
I only left Jack
a short time ago,

00:23.816 --> 00:25.985
and I miss him already.

00:25.985 --> 00:27.862
He'll be gone for two months,

00:27.862 --> 00:29.905
but he's training Mounties,
not fighting,

00:29.905 --> 00:31.532
so I don't have
the same concerns

00:31.532 --> 00:34.075
as when he left
for the Northern Territories.

00:34.075 --> 00:35.410
Still...

00:35.410 --> 00:38.205
I anxiously await
the day he returns

00:38.205 --> 00:40.791
and we'll be together again.

00:44.003 --> 00:45.921
Here she comes!

00:48.340 --> 00:50.049
[LAUGHING]

00:54.513 --> 00:56.097
Whoa!

00:56.097 --> 00:57.975
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

00:57.975 --> 01:00.185
Here she is!

01:00.185 --> 01:02.396
Welcome back.
Thank you, Lee. Thank you.

01:02.396 --> 01:03.438
You're welcome.

01:03.438 --> 01:05.315
Oh. We've missed you.

01:05.315 --> 01:06.984
How was your honeymoon?

01:06.984 --> 01:08.986
Oh, it couldn't
have been better.

01:08.986 --> 01:10.905
Ah! Who needs Chicago?

01:10.905 --> 01:12.656
It was really
just the two of us,

01:12.656 --> 01:13.866
finding our way.

01:13.866 --> 01:16.117
Oh, it sounds
so romantic.

01:16.117 --> 01:17.912
Oh! How did everything
go at school?

01:17.912 --> 01:19.287
[SIGHS]
Oh!

01:21.122 --> 01:22.708
Welcome back.

01:22.708 --> 01:24.083
Oh...

01:24.083 --> 01:25.961
okay.

01:27.963 --> 01:29.214
Uh, Mrs. Stanton?

01:29.214 --> 01:30.716
May I have a word?

01:30.716 --> 01:33.010
Of course,
Mr. Jenkins.

01:33.010 --> 01:34.845
Now, what did I miss?

01:34.845 --> 01:36.013
The children missed you.

01:36.013 --> 01:37.681
I missed them too.

01:37.681 --> 01:38.807
What is it?

01:38.807 --> 01:40.308
I wanted
to inform you that,

01:40.308 --> 01:42.101
with a little luck,
in a few days,

01:42.101 --> 01:43.353
the bank should reopen.

01:43.353 --> 01:45.480
Oh, well, we're not certain

01:45.480 --> 01:47.858
that Mr. Gowen's investor
is going to come through.

01:47.858 --> 01:49.902
No, it's someone else
I've lined up.

01:49.902 --> 01:51.486
His name's Joshua Baxter.

01:51.486 --> 01:53.238
Very wealthy.

01:53.238 --> 01:54.907
Oh, well,
that's wonderful news.

01:54.907 --> 01:55.991
Is this for certain?

01:55.991 --> 01:57.826
No, but we're in
negotiations.

01:57.826 --> 02:00.704
He's coming by later this
afternoon. He wants to meet you.

02:00.704 --> 02:03.082
Absolutely. Please,
bring him by my office.

02:03.082 --> 02:05.042
Excellent.

02:05.834 --> 02:08.045
[♪♪♪]

02:12.716 --> 02:14.718
[CRUNCHES]

02:14.718 --> 02:16.095
I wish my mom
would pack me

02:16.095 --> 02:17.888
something to snack on
besides apples.

02:17.888 --> 02:20.140
My mom says as soon as
the bank opens again,

02:20.140 --> 02:21.767
we won't
have to make do anymore.

02:21.767 --> 02:24.394
Good morning, everyone!

02:24.394 --> 02:26.271
ALL:
Good morning!

02:26.271 --> 02:28.816
It's so nice to be back.
I missed all of you.

02:28.816 --> 02:31.026
I missed you too,
Miss Thatcher.

02:31.026 --> 02:32.235
[GASPS]

02:32.235 --> 02:34.446
I mean, Mrs. Thornton.

02:34.446 --> 02:36.490
[LAUGHS]
It's okay.
I know my new name

02:36.490 --> 02:38.199
might take a while
to get used to.

02:38.199 --> 02:39.284
We all missed you.

02:39.284 --> 02:41.996
Yeah. Mrs. Blakely
yells a lot.

02:41.996 --> 02:45.582
And why, I wonder, did
Mrs. Blakely find it necessary

02:45.582 --> 02:48.335
to raise her voice
while I was away?

02:48.335 --> 02:50.545
I was good.

02:50.545 --> 02:52.840
[CHUCKLES]
[APPLE CRUNCHES]

02:52.840 --> 02:56.426
Robert! You know better
than to eat during class time.

02:56.426 --> 02:58.012
Please save that for recess.

02:58.012 --> 02:59.721
I'll just throw it away.

02:59.721 --> 03:01.348
You shouldn't
waste food

03:01.348 --> 03:04.183
when the Mercantile's shelves
are practically empty.

03:04.183 --> 03:05.560
But they still have candy.

03:05.560 --> 03:07.562
Mr. Yost says
candy is a luxury,

03:07.562 --> 03:09.314
and you can't buy it
on credit.

03:09.314 --> 03:11.566
It's been a difficult time
for everyone,

03:11.566 --> 03:13.986
but, hopefully, the bank
will be reopening soon,

03:13.986 --> 03:16.321
and I heard
that two different people

03:16.321 --> 03:17.990
might invest money in it.

03:17.990 --> 03:20.450
What do you mean, "invest"?

03:20.450 --> 03:22.119
That's a business term
that means

03:22.119 --> 03:24.663
putting money into something
to get more money back.

03:24.663 --> 03:26.331
My mom says
the bank's in trouble

03:26.331 --> 03:28.125
because they did
a bad job of that.

03:28.125 --> 03:31.003
Do all businesses invest?

03:31.003 --> 03:33.338
In one way or another.

03:34.673 --> 03:37.509
Maybe we should learn
how businesses work.

03:37.509 --> 03:40.095
ALL:
Yeah!

03:40.095 --> 03:41.889
Hmm.

03:41.889 --> 03:44.099
[♪♪♪]

03:56.778 --> 03:58.572
Hey.

04:01.366 --> 04:03.911
Hey, this isn't a flophouse.

04:04.995 --> 04:06.287
I'm warning you.

04:06.287 --> 04:09.041
Get up, or I'll lock you
in here for good.

04:09.041 --> 04:10.500
I said get--

04:10.500 --> 04:12.169
[GASPS]
[GUN COCKS]

04:15.296 --> 04:18.299
Never sneak up
on a sleeping woman.

04:18.299 --> 04:20.677
AJ Foster.

04:20.677 --> 04:22.888
I wondered if
I'd see you again.

04:24.347 --> 04:26.474
What're you
gonna do with that?

04:32.522 --> 04:33.565
Take it.

04:33.565 --> 04:36.151
I'm turning myself in.

04:36.151 --> 04:38.361
[♪♪♪]

04:40.197 --> 04:42.407
[♪♪♪]

05:01.093 --> 05:03.303
[♪♪♪]

05:03.303 --> 05:06.890
After a year on the run,
you decide to turn yourself in?

05:06.890 --> 05:08.850
Well, it's not easy
being a fugitive,

05:08.850 --> 05:10.936
always looking
over your shoulder.

05:10.936 --> 05:12.271
Why'd you come here?

05:12.271 --> 05:14.273
You could've
surrendered to any lawman.

05:14.273 --> 05:15.732
Well, I suppose,

05:15.732 --> 05:17.734
but you were the one
who arrested me.

05:17.734 --> 05:19.486
Call me loyal.

05:19.486 --> 05:22.363
I'd call you a lot of things,
but loyal isn't one of them.

05:22.363 --> 05:24.365
[CHUCKLES]
Come on, Bill.

05:24.365 --> 05:26.994
Thought you'd be
happy to see me.

05:26.994 --> 05:30.664
I'm always happy
when a fugitive faces justice.

05:30.664 --> 05:33.125
Is that the only reason
you're glad I'm here?

05:33.125 --> 05:34.251
The only.

05:34.251 --> 05:36.419
Oh, come on!
Don't be like that.

05:36.419 --> 05:38.255
I tried to contact you.

05:39.506 --> 05:40.757
It's true.

05:40.757 --> 05:42.467
In fact, ugh,

05:42.467 --> 05:45.304
I was near Hope Valley once
and I almost came to see you,

05:45.304 --> 05:47.264
but I didn't know
how you'd react.

05:48.890 --> 05:51.018
[DOOR CLANGS]
[KEYS JINGLING]

05:57.149 --> 05:58.984
[SIGHS]

06:01.111 --> 06:03.113
ELIZABETH:
So this class project
is about

06:03.113 --> 06:05.406
showing my students
how real businesses work.

06:05.406 --> 06:07.326
There'd be at least
one student assigned

06:07.326 --> 06:08.869
to every participating
business,

06:08.869 --> 06:10.620
matched up
by student interest,

06:10.620 --> 06:12.413
and it's only for one day.

06:12.413 --> 06:14.415
Sure. I'll do it.

06:14.415 --> 06:16.126
Well, I can't wait

06:16.126 --> 06:19.504
to teach a clever child
how to design high fashion.

06:19.504 --> 06:22.632
And how it helps the town's
economy, of course.

06:22.632 --> 06:24.259
That's the spirit.

06:24.259 --> 06:25.760
Uh, who else will participate?

06:25.760 --> 06:27.762
Lee will.
I will?

06:27.762 --> 06:29.681
I mean, yes.
Of course, I will.

06:29.681 --> 06:31.808
I just-- I'm not so sure
your kids are gonna

06:31.808 --> 06:33.227
find what I do
interesting.

06:33.227 --> 06:34.477
Nonsense!

06:34.477 --> 06:36.479
You're the town's
biggest employer.

06:36.479 --> 06:39.274
You, Lee Coulter,

06:39.274 --> 06:40.942
are fascinating.

06:40.942 --> 06:42.443
[LAUGHS]

06:42.443 --> 06:44.487
[COUGHING]

06:44.487 --> 06:46.740
Excuse me.
You can count me in, of course.

06:46.740 --> 06:48.742
Great. Thank you.

06:48.742 --> 06:50.285
Carson?

06:50.285 --> 06:52.579
Of course. Is there anything
we need to know?

06:52.579 --> 06:54.413
Not really.
Go about your average day

06:54.413 --> 06:56.333
and let the students
watch what you do.

06:56.333 --> 06:59.044
Please sign this if
you're willing to participate.

07:00.128 --> 07:01.880
Yep.
Why don't you just sign me up?

07:01.880 --> 07:03.006
Mm-hmm.
Okay.

07:05.550 --> 07:06.843
[DOOR OPENS]

07:06.843 --> 07:09.221
BILL:
Hey.

07:09.221 --> 07:10.722
I need a meal
for a prisoner.

07:10.722 --> 07:12.432
Oh, sure.
I'll pour you some soup.

07:12.432 --> 07:14.393
Uh, what's the special today?

07:14.393 --> 07:15.643
It's gonna be meat loaf,

07:15.643 --> 07:17.562
but it won't be ready
for a few hours.

07:17.562 --> 07:18.897
Oh.

07:18.897 --> 07:20.399
Is it for the prisoner?

07:20.399 --> 07:22.067
Why?

07:22.067 --> 07:25.987
Because you've never requested
my special for a prisoner.

07:25.987 --> 07:27.697
Just pour me the soup.

07:29.574 --> 07:31.743
Who's been arrested?

07:31.743 --> 07:33.453
AJ Foster.

07:33.453 --> 07:34.662
Ah-ha.

07:34.662 --> 07:36.456
Ah-ha?
What does that mean?

07:36.456 --> 07:39.626
[CHUCKLING]
It means "ah-ha."

07:39.626 --> 07:41.420
I'll pour you a little extra.

07:41.420 --> 07:43.504
Just the normal amount
is fine, thank you.

07:43.504 --> 07:45.299
Mm-hmm.
[POURING SOUP]

07:45.299 --> 07:47.759
Whatever you're thinking,
it's just in your head.

07:47.759 --> 07:50.137
Whatever you say.

07:53.140 --> 07:55.183
Each one of these businesses
has agreed

07:55.183 --> 07:56.601
to let at least one of you

07:56.601 --> 07:58.895
spend the day with them
to see how they operate.

07:58.895 --> 08:01.106
Isn't that exciting?
ALL: Yeah!

08:01.106 --> 08:03.024
Now, who is interested
in what?

08:03.024 --> 08:04.401
Yes, Robert?

08:04.401 --> 08:05.860
I want Dr. Shepherd!

08:05.860 --> 08:07.946
Oh. Very good.

08:07.946 --> 08:09.990
"Robert."

08:09.990 --> 08:11.325
Yes, Emily?

08:11.325 --> 08:12.826
Could I go
to the dress shop?

08:12.826 --> 08:14.953
I want to become a designer
when I grow up.

08:14.953 --> 08:17.456
Then that's
the place for you.

08:17.456 --> 08:19.374
"Emily."

08:20.959 --> 08:22.627
Now, Coulter Lumber

08:22.627 --> 08:25.546
is one of the most important
companies in the whole town.

08:25.546 --> 08:26.840
Who is interested

08:26.840 --> 08:28.925
in spending tomorrow
with Mr. Coulter?

08:28.925 --> 08:30.260
I am!

08:30.260 --> 08:32.137
Great! Cody.

08:36.266 --> 08:37.558
Yes, Opal?

08:37.558 --> 08:39.269
I want the Mercantile!

08:39.269 --> 08:41.313
Of course.

08:42.647 --> 08:45.442
They have
lots of candy there.

08:45.442 --> 08:47.277
Yes, Hattie?

08:47.277 --> 08:48.987
Ice cream shop, please.

08:48.987 --> 08:51.490
Clever girl.

08:51.490 --> 08:54.326
Oh! Should've said
ice cream shop.

08:54.326 --> 08:56.536
[♪♪♪]

08:59.622 --> 09:01.500
The soup is delicious.

09:02.417 --> 09:04.252
Yes, it is.

09:06.129 --> 09:08.215
Come on, Bill.
I know you're mad at me,

09:08.215 --> 09:10.509
but why can't we just talk?

09:10.509 --> 09:12.802
I'm not mad, and no.

09:13.720 --> 09:15.680
This is just silly.

09:15.680 --> 09:18.641
I mean, we're both eating lunch.
Why can't we eat together?

09:18.641 --> 09:20.935
Because you're on that side,
and I'm not.

09:22.103 --> 09:24.189
Besides, what's there
to talk about?

09:24.189 --> 09:27.526
You know exactly
what there is to talk about.

09:27.526 --> 09:29.736
[♪♪♪]

09:41.039 --> 09:42.582
Wanna talk?

09:42.582 --> 09:44.459
Talk.

09:45.960 --> 09:47.754
What happened
between us...

09:47.754 --> 09:49.548
I arrested you,
you escaped,

09:49.548 --> 09:51.216
that's all there was.

09:51.216 --> 09:53.134
Well, you...

09:53.134 --> 09:55.053
you left out a part.

09:55.053 --> 09:57.180
Big part.

09:57.180 --> 09:58.639
We kissed.

09:58.639 --> 10:00.517
I think
you kissed me.

10:00.517 --> 10:02.936
[LAUGHS]
I think I recall
that you enjoyed it.

10:04.020 --> 10:05.813
Why can't
you just admit it?

10:05.813 --> 10:09.484
Bill, that kiss meant
something to both of us.

10:09.484 --> 10:11.736
What do you think
it meant?

10:11.736 --> 10:15.532
I think it meant that
if circumstances were different,

10:15.532 --> 10:17.033
we could have been different.

10:17.033 --> 10:18.743
Well, they're not,
and we're not.

10:18.743 --> 10:19.994
But it's not too late.

10:19.994 --> 10:23.081
Why do you think
I turned myself in?

10:24.207 --> 10:26.793
I just wanna
put this behind me,

10:26.793 --> 10:28.587
and...and start fresh.

10:33.674 --> 10:36.636
I don't know about you,
but I've had enough.

10:37.678 --> 10:39.222
[SIGHS]

10:40.765 --> 10:43.393
I'm of the opinion that
there is no better investment

10:43.393 --> 10:45.728
than a small town
with real growth potential.

10:45.728 --> 10:47.272
I'm happy to hear that.

10:47.272 --> 10:50.024
I'm not one for false modesty,
so I'll just lay it out.

10:50.024 --> 10:51.692
I've got a fantastic
track record

10:51.692 --> 10:54.195
when it comes to picking
which towns to invest in.

10:54.195 --> 10:55.530
How do you choose?

10:55.530 --> 10:57.949
Not by looking
into a crystal ball.

10:57.949 --> 11:00.577
I look at a map
and I ask myself:

11:00.577 --> 11:02.287
"Can this town
become the hub

11:02.287 --> 11:04.498
for all the other towns
around it?"

11:04.498 --> 11:06.291
This town can
definitely be that.

11:06.291 --> 11:08.376
But it all comes down
to the people

11:08.376 --> 11:10.420
and their desire
for something more.

11:10.420 --> 11:11.630
Well, you won't find

11:11.630 --> 11:13.714
a better group
of hard-working citizens

11:13.714 --> 11:15.008
than here in Hope Valley.

11:16.176 --> 11:17.927
Let me ask you this,
Madame Mayor:

11:17.927 --> 11:19.720
do you consider yourself
pro-growth?

11:19.720 --> 11:21.931
Oh, I fought to bring
a railway depot here.

11:21.931 --> 11:23.975
I certainly want
my town to prosper.

11:23.975 --> 11:26.520
If I become majority
stakeholder in the bank,

11:26.520 --> 11:28.687
I wanna make sure
we're partners

11:28.687 --> 11:31.650
in promoting
new businesses and growth.

11:31.650 --> 11:33.401
Uh...

11:33.401 --> 11:35.320
what kind of businesses
and growth

11:35.320 --> 11:36.779
are you talking about?

11:37.947 --> 11:41.535
Well, whatever helps
this town prosper.

11:41.535 --> 11:43.662
[♪♪♪]

11:45.038 --> 11:47.582
Uh, I can assure you
that we are all for growth

11:47.582 --> 11:50.168
and sound investments.

11:59.010 --> 12:02.556
All right. Now, remember
to listen and observe,

12:02.556 --> 12:03.848
but don't get in the way,

12:03.848 --> 12:06.267
and I will be
checking in on you.

12:06.267 --> 12:09.479
Can we go now?

12:09.479 --> 12:10.855
ELIZABETH:
Yes!

12:10.855 --> 12:12.899
ALL:
Yay!

12:12.899 --> 12:14.359
[ALL CHEERING]

12:14.359 --> 12:16.570
[♪♪♪]

12:20.198 --> 12:22.659
Just got a wire saying
I'm supposed to escort you

12:22.659 --> 12:25.412
to Cape Fullerton
day after tomorrow.

12:33.794 --> 12:35.880
[AJ PACING]

12:37.674 --> 12:40.176
Would you stop that pacing?
It's annoying.

12:40.176 --> 12:41.678
Sorry.
Not used to

12:41.678 --> 12:43.971
being cooped up
in a jail cell.

12:43.971 --> 12:45.973
[DOOR OPENS]

12:45.973 --> 12:47.559
Good morning, Bill.

12:47.559 --> 12:49.227
BILL:
Morning.

12:49.227 --> 12:52.606
Heading to the office.
Thought I'd drop off breakfast.

12:52.606 --> 12:54.148
Good morning, AJ.

12:54.148 --> 12:55.734
Oh, good morning,
Mrs. Stanton.

12:55.734 --> 12:57.193
BILL:
It's Mayor Stanton now.

12:57.193 --> 12:58.903
Oh! Wow.

12:58.903 --> 13:01.155
I've never had a mayor
cook for me before.

13:01.155 --> 13:03.241
Thank you,
it's been delicious.

13:03.241 --> 13:04.659
You're welcome.

13:04.659 --> 13:07.370
You didn't have to do this.
Oh, it's no bother.

13:07.370 --> 13:10.331
So how did the meeting with
the investor go yesterday?

13:10.331 --> 13:13.376
[SIGHS]
Well...

13:13.376 --> 13:15.002
To be honest,

13:15.002 --> 13:16.379
I don't have a good feeling.

13:16.379 --> 13:17.880
Why's that?

13:17.880 --> 13:20.007
ABIGAIL:
There's something
I don't trust.

13:20.007 --> 13:21.593
Really?
What's this guy's name?

13:21.593 --> 13:23.386
Joshua Baxter.

13:23.386 --> 13:25.555
Joshua Baxter?

13:25.555 --> 13:27.140
You have ears
like a bat.

13:27.140 --> 13:29.934
A single woman needs to develop
every one of her senses.

13:29.934 --> 13:31.770
Especially when
they're a fugitive.

13:33.104 --> 13:36.566
ABIGAIL:
AJ, do you know
this Joshua Baxter?

13:36.566 --> 13:38.318
Well, I can't say for sure,

13:38.318 --> 13:40.654
but his name
kind of rings a bell.

13:40.654 --> 13:43.948
Maybe if she saw him,
it would jog her memory.

13:43.948 --> 13:48.077
What? No. I'm not letting
her out of my sight.

13:48.077 --> 13:50.705
All you have to do
is take a look at him,

13:50.705 --> 13:52.915
then you might remember
how you've heard--

13:52.915 --> 13:54.917
I don't think this
is a good idea at all.

13:54.917 --> 13:56.252
You have a better one?

13:56.252 --> 13:57.587
Well, what's in it for me?

13:57.587 --> 13:59.589
How about you're lucky to--?
Bill.

14:00.757 --> 14:03.510
What would it take
for you to help us?

14:03.510 --> 14:05.720
[♪♪♪]

14:07.639 --> 14:09.140
[DOOR OPENS]

14:09.140 --> 14:11.017
LEE:
So? What do you think?

14:11.017 --> 14:13.353
What do you do
with all the lumber?

14:13.353 --> 14:14.771
Well, we stack it,

14:14.771 --> 14:16.230
we dry it,
and bundle it.

14:16.230 --> 14:17.816
How much do you
sell it for?

14:17.816 --> 14:20.193
That depends on what we sell
and where we sell it.

14:20.193 --> 14:22.862
And then, when it's ready,
we put it on a railcar,

14:22.862 --> 14:25.865
and before you know it,
the customer gets their order.

14:25.865 --> 14:28.075
Which reminds me. Michael,
are we on schedule

14:28.075 --> 14:29.869
to get that order
to Port Henderson?

14:29.869 --> 14:31.954
It'll be on the train by 5.
Excellent.

14:31.954 --> 14:33.540
I see you have
a sidekick today.

14:33.540 --> 14:35.625
Yes, Mrs. Thornton's
class project.

14:35.625 --> 14:37.711
Young Cody'll be
learning the ropes.

14:37.711 --> 14:39.128
Isn't that right?

14:39.128 --> 14:41.756
I want to be an important
businessman one day.

14:41.756 --> 14:43.717
Well, you're learning
from the best.

14:44.843 --> 14:47.220
All right,
what do we got here?

14:48.054 --> 14:49.848
Uh...

14:49.848 --> 14:52.433
Actually, you know, I was
just about to order lunch.

14:52.433 --> 14:55.687
Are you supposed to be having
lunch with your friends, or...?

14:55.687 --> 14:57.313
Shouldn't I
have lunch with you?

14:57.313 --> 14:59.357
I mean, lunch is part
of your day, right?

14:59.357 --> 15:02.276
Yeah. Sometimes, it's
the best part of my day.

15:03.319 --> 15:05.988
All right, then.
Let's do lunch!

15:05.988 --> 15:08.991
[♪♪♪]

15:08.991 --> 15:11.077
Well, between the two
potential investors,

15:11.077 --> 15:13.162
there's a good chance one
will come through.

15:13.162 --> 15:16.332
I have my reservations about
who Mr. Jenkins brought in.

15:16.332 --> 15:18.000
But we'll see
about the other.

15:18.000 --> 15:20.002
I know you want
all this to be over.

15:20.002 --> 15:21.295
We all do,

15:21.295 --> 15:23.631
but you are doing
an amazing job

15:23.631 --> 15:25.091
keeping the town calm.

15:25.091 --> 15:26.426
Thank you.

15:26.426 --> 15:28.636
[♪♪♪]

15:32.306 --> 15:33.558
That looks like
her now.

15:34.601 --> 15:35.894
Wish me luck.

15:35.894 --> 15:36.936
She has a chauffeur.

15:36.936 --> 15:38.479
I'd say you're
already in luck.

15:38.479 --> 15:40.147
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

15:40.147 --> 15:43.025
Elizabeth, that Emily
is such a doll.

15:43.025 --> 15:44.485
Isn't she?
Yes.

15:44.485 --> 15:46.987
[DOTTIE SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY]

15:46.987 --> 15:49.031
Mrs. Preston?
Oh, that's me, darling.

15:49.031 --> 15:51.409
Abigail Stanton,
Mayor of Hope Valley.

15:51.409 --> 15:52.827
Well, hello.

15:52.827 --> 15:55.705
What a quaint little place
you have here.

15:55.705 --> 15:58.458
Quaint,
and so much more.

15:59.584 --> 16:02.253
Is-- Is that
Elizabeth Thatcher?

16:02.253 --> 16:04.338
ABIGAIL:
Well, yes.

16:04.338 --> 16:06.716
Actually, it's
Elizabeth Thornton now.

16:06.716 --> 16:08.843
Oh. Excuse me.

16:08.843 --> 16:09.928
Elizabeth!

16:11.387 --> 16:12.764
Excuse me.

16:12.764 --> 16:14.348
I can't believe it!

16:14.348 --> 16:16.100
Mrs. Preston!

16:16.100 --> 16:17.518
Elizabeth!

16:17.518 --> 16:19.604
I hear you're
a married lady now.

16:19.604 --> 16:22.022
I always knew you'd
be quite the catch.

16:22.022 --> 16:23.900
How do you two
know each other?

16:23.900 --> 16:25.276
From Hamilton.

16:25.276 --> 16:27.445
My sisters and I grew up
with your son.

16:27.445 --> 16:29.363
Mrs. Preston is
a friend of the family.

16:29.363 --> 16:31.908
You're not a little girl
anymore, call me Greta.

16:31.908 --> 16:35.453
I see you've already made
some acquaintances, Greta.

16:35.453 --> 16:37.037
Well, yes.
New and old.

16:37.037 --> 16:39.039
We were practically
neighbors.

16:39.039 --> 16:41.459
Oh, right.
You both are from Hamilton.

16:41.459 --> 16:43.628
Elizabeth and my son
went to the same school.

16:43.628 --> 16:45.630
She would come over
and help him with his homework.

16:45.630 --> 16:46.881
I paid her
with cookies.

16:46.881 --> 16:48.007
[ALL LAUGH]

16:48.007 --> 16:50.593
Elizabeth
is our teacher here.

16:50.593 --> 16:52.386
Well, of course.
Perfect.

16:52.386 --> 16:53.930
HENRY:
Well, shall we, ladies?

16:53.930 --> 16:55.431
Yes.

16:55.431 --> 16:57.976
We'll talk soon.
Yes.

16:57.976 --> 17:00.645
I think luck is definitely
on your side now.

17:00.645 --> 17:02.772
[EXHALES HEAVILY[

17:02.772 --> 17:04.691
[LAUGHS]

17:05.733 --> 17:07.819
[CHAIR SQUEAKING]

17:09.445 --> 17:11.531
[SQUEAKING CONTINUES]

17:18.454 --> 17:20.874
I wanna be a doctor
when I grow up.

17:20.874 --> 17:22.500
Good!

17:22.500 --> 17:26.045
Well, study really hard.

17:26.045 --> 17:27.755
When's something
gonna happen?

17:27.755 --> 17:30.257
Oh, Mr. Lawson's coming by
in a couple hours

17:30.257 --> 17:31.801
to have some stitches removed.

17:31.801 --> 17:34.261
Two hours?

17:34.261 --> 17:36.263
Robert, we count it
a good thing

17:36.263 --> 17:38.808
when there's no medical
emergencies in town.

17:40.059 --> 17:41.895
Doctors make
a lot of money, right?

17:41.895 --> 17:43.813
Some do, yep.
Some don't.

17:43.813 --> 17:45.189
How much do you charge?

17:45.189 --> 17:47.358
Well, that all depends
on what I do,

17:47.358 --> 17:49.068
and what they can pay.

17:49.068 --> 17:50.403
Nobody gets turned away.

17:50.403 --> 17:53.072
Sometimes, we don't
charge anything at all.

17:53.072 --> 17:54.824
You work for free?

17:54.824 --> 17:57.284
Occasionally, yeah.

17:57.284 --> 18:00.162
No wonder this town's broke.

18:00.162 --> 18:01.873
[♪♪♪]

18:03.624 --> 18:04.959
Come along, young man.

18:04.959 --> 18:06.502
You can help me
fold towels.

18:06.502 --> 18:08.004
What does
folding towels

18:08.004 --> 18:10.048
have to do with
being a doctor?

18:10.048 --> 18:12.550
You'd be surprised.

18:18.347 --> 18:20.892
Abigail and I have made
arrangements for you to meet

18:20.892 --> 18:23.310
with some of the merchants
after our meeting.

18:23.310 --> 18:26.146
Good. I want to see every nook
and cranny of Hope Valley.

18:26.146 --> 18:29.149
I need to be convinced there's
real growth potential here.

18:29.149 --> 18:30.651
I think you will be.

18:30.651 --> 18:33.071
Henry has already
filled me in on the history

18:33.071 --> 18:36.908
and statistics
and little secrets.

18:36.908 --> 18:40.453
I wasn't aware that Hope Valley
had any little secrets.

18:40.453 --> 18:44.248
Oh, darling, every town
has its little secrets.

18:45.416 --> 18:48.168
Well, we believe
in full disclosure here,

18:48.168 --> 18:50.046
which is why I need
to be...

18:50.046 --> 18:51.380
honest with you.

18:51.380 --> 18:53.132
Oh. Sounds ominous.

18:53.132 --> 18:54.842
There's another investor
in town

18:54.842 --> 18:56.803
looking into
funding the bank.

18:56.803 --> 18:59.179
[♪♪♪]

18:59.179 --> 19:00.890
You didn't
tell me this, Henry.

19:00.890 --> 19:03.017
Because I wasn't
aware at the time.

19:04.602 --> 19:06.813
I hope you're not
using me as a ploy

19:06.813 --> 19:08.564
to entice
this other investor.

19:08.564 --> 19:09.899
I don't do things
like that.

19:09.899 --> 19:12.110
Because I am nobody's
bargaining chip,

19:12.110 --> 19:13.235
and I can I assure you

19:13.235 --> 19:14.779
I will ride off
into the sunset

19:14.779 --> 19:16.489
if I get even get
a whiff of that.

19:16.489 --> 19:18.240
You won't.

19:19.575 --> 19:21.661
What's this other
investor's name?

19:21.661 --> 19:23.621
Joshua Baxter.

19:23.621 --> 19:25.205
Never heard of him.

19:25.205 --> 19:26.582
Does he know I'm here?

19:26.582 --> 19:27.708
I don't think he does.

19:27.708 --> 19:29.293
Well, tell him.

19:29.293 --> 19:32.296
[CLEARS THROAT]
I want everything
on the up-and-up.

19:32.296 --> 19:33.547
And if I run into him,

19:33.547 --> 19:36.258
I will definitely
introduce myself.

19:36.258 --> 19:39.637
I can let myself out.
Good day, Mayor.

19:41.139 --> 19:43.850
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

19:44.934 --> 19:47.103
So where's this Baxter from?

19:47.103 --> 19:48.855
I don't know.

19:48.855 --> 19:52.358
He says he invests in towns
all over the country.

19:52.358 --> 19:54.902
Apparently, he's in the market
for another one,

19:54.902 --> 19:56.946
and we might fit the bill.

19:56.946 --> 19:59.448
You seem, uh...
wary of him.

19:59.448 --> 20:03.285
Not wary
as much as cautious.

20:04.453 --> 20:06.039
Well, the goal here

20:06.039 --> 20:09.167
is to have Hope Valley's bank
be flush again,

20:09.167 --> 20:10.877
so two investors gives us

20:10.877 --> 20:13.129
two opportunities
to do just that.

20:14.213 --> 20:16.132
Let's hope.

20:20.302 --> 20:23.181
ROSEMARY:
To become an exceptional
dress designer,

20:23.181 --> 20:25.599
you need to have
an eye for fashion,

20:25.599 --> 20:27.852
which means
you need to be able to

20:27.852 --> 20:31.647
blend color,
and fabric, and style

20:31.647 --> 20:35.234
to make
one perfect outfit.

20:35.234 --> 20:37.403
I can do that.
Wonderful!

20:37.403 --> 20:39.488
Now, here...

20:39.488 --> 20:42.241
is one item of clothing,

20:42.241 --> 20:45.828
a white silk scarf

20:45.828 --> 20:47.121
to start you off.

20:47.121 --> 20:48.748
Now, I want you to show me

20:48.748 --> 20:50.875
how you would
build an ensemble

20:50.875 --> 20:52.877
based on this scarf...

20:52.877 --> 20:55.004
while I hang some dresses
on the back rack.

20:55.004 --> 20:56.714
You can use
anything in the shop.

20:56.714 --> 20:58.507
Okay.

20:58.507 --> 21:00.718
[♪♪♪]

21:11.478 --> 21:12.772
I'm done!

21:12.772 --> 21:14.857
Already? Okay.
Let me see.

21:14.857 --> 21:16.067
[GASPS]
Oh...

21:16.067 --> 21:17.860
...kay.

21:17.860 --> 21:19.987
[SIGHS]

21:19.987 --> 21:23.323
So the color scheme

21:23.323 --> 21:25.284
really works...

21:25.284 --> 21:26.786
sort of.

21:26.786 --> 21:30.081
Pinstripe and plaid...

21:30.081 --> 21:35.920
We may need a small lesson
on patterns.

21:35.920 --> 21:38.214
[THEATRICALLY]
Patterns.

21:38.214 --> 21:42.301
Yes.
Oh...patterns.

21:46.847 --> 21:48.724
Mm.

21:48.724 --> 21:50.601
Mm.

21:54.188 --> 21:56.315
Ah.

21:56.315 --> 21:58.651
Ah.

21:58.651 --> 22:00.861
[♪♪♪]

22:04.824 --> 22:06.784
What do you usually
do in the afternoon?

22:06.784 --> 22:08.452
Mm.

22:08.452 --> 22:11.164
Well, to be honest with you,
it's not very interesting.

22:11.164 --> 22:13.958
Once I know everything is
running smoothly at the mill,

22:13.958 --> 22:16.585
I, uh, I come back here,
and I do paperwork.

22:16.585 --> 22:17.795
What's paperwork?

22:17.795 --> 22:18.963
I go over the ledgers,

22:18.963 --> 22:20.714
and make sure
everything checks out.

22:20.714 --> 22:23.425
You know, credits, debits,
that sort of thing.

22:24.927 --> 22:28.097
Yeah. Yeah, you're right,
it's pretty boring.

22:28.097 --> 22:29.515
You know...

22:29.515 --> 22:31.725
your, uh, your school hour
is just about up.

22:31.725 --> 22:34.270
You don't have to stick around
if you don't want to.

22:34.270 --> 22:35.855
I wanna stay.
But don't you

22:35.855 --> 22:38.065
and your friends
play baseball after school?

22:38.065 --> 22:39.275
I can do that anytime.

22:39.275 --> 22:42.360
I wanna learn
about the...um...

22:42.360 --> 22:45.363
The ledgers?
Right. The ledgers.

22:45.363 --> 22:47.407
[LAUGHS]
Really?

22:47.407 --> 22:49.994
You wanna learn
about the ledgers.

22:49.994 --> 22:52.955
Okay. Bring it on
over here.

22:53.873 --> 22:55.082
You know what?

22:55.082 --> 22:58.336
It's really not
all that complicated.

22:58.336 --> 23:00.420
Think of it as...

23:01.588 --> 23:04.967
Credits, debits.
Money in, money out.

23:04.967 --> 23:07.511
Right? Money in,
good, we like that.

23:07.511 --> 23:09.889
Money out, bad,
we don't like that.

23:09.889 --> 23:12.225
So here.
You good at math?

23:12.225 --> 23:13.517
Okay.

23:17.021 --> 23:18.647
We haven't got all day!

23:18.647 --> 23:19.857
DOTTIE:
Just a moment.

23:21.859 --> 23:23.527
You cannot rush beauty, Bill.

23:25.988 --> 23:28.366
Come on out, AJ.

23:29.033 --> 23:31.244
[♪♪♪]

23:34.454 --> 23:35.873
Well?

23:37.917 --> 23:39.877
Well, I think--

23:39.877 --> 23:41.254
This is fine.

23:41.254 --> 23:43.130
DOTTIE [SCOFFS]:
Fine?

23:43.130 --> 23:45.716
She looks absolutely stunning.

23:45.716 --> 23:48.635
Thanks to you.

23:48.635 --> 23:51.138
So, what do you think?

23:51.138 --> 23:52.890
Well...

23:54.474 --> 23:56.143
I think we should get going.

23:56.143 --> 23:58.354
[♪♪♪]

23:59.897 --> 24:01.065
[DOOR CLOSES]

24:01.065 --> 24:02.858
[SIGHS]

24:02.858 --> 24:04.526
I don't know
why I bother.

24:04.526 --> 24:06.444
NED:
People can
move about the store

24:06.444 --> 24:08.072
choose the items
that they need,

24:08.072 --> 24:10.532
and then, when a customer
is ready to pay,

24:10.532 --> 24:12.868
I ring them up,
using this register.

24:12.868 --> 24:14.036
Any questions?

24:14.036 --> 24:15.788
What are those?

24:15.788 --> 24:18.582
Uh...those
are pickled eggs.

24:18.582 --> 24:20.126
They taste like pickles?

24:20.126 --> 24:21.210
Yes. They're very tasty.

24:21.210 --> 24:22.628
Would you like
to try one?

24:22.628 --> 24:24.462
Yes? All right.

24:24.462 --> 24:27.674
Now, I pickle these myself,

24:27.674 --> 24:30.844
and I am very proud
of the recipe.

24:30.844 --> 24:33.347
[♪♪♪]

24:33.347 --> 24:34.890
There you are.

24:39.686 --> 24:41.063
Do you like it?

24:41.063 --> 24:43.774
It's delicious!

24:43.774 --> 24:45.525
It's good, isn't it?

24:47.485 --> 24:49.989
Now remember,
we wait in the saloon.

24:49.989 --> 24:52.032
When Baxter comes in,
you take a good look

24:52.032 --> 24:53.742
at him to see if
you recognize him,

24:53.742 --> 24:55.453
then we walk out.
Got it?

24:55.453 --> 24:57.163
Got it.
You're sure?

24:57.163 --> 24:59.748
Easy as pie!

24:59.748 --> 25:02.418
Henry Gowen?

25:04.628 --> 25:05.796
Miss Foster.

25:05.796 --> 25:07.256
Now is not the time, AJ.

25:07.256 --> 25:08.548
I think now is the time.

25:08.548 --> 25:10.592
Look at you.
A free man.

25:10.592 --> 25:11.885
Unbelievable.

25:11.885 --> 25:14.054
I could say
the same about you,

25:14.054 --> 25:15.973
which does
beg the question:

25:15.973 --> 25:18.225
What is she doing
out on the streets, Bill?

25:18.225 --> 25:19.685
Oh, that's
a charming question

25:19.685 --> 25:21.228
coming from a man
who conspired

25:21.228 --> 25:23.105
with the people
who tried to kill me.

25:23.105 --> 25:25.316
I did my time,
which is something

25:25.316 --> 25:27.318
you'll get a feel for
soon enough,

25:27.318 --> 25:29.403
should our Sheriff
decide to do his job.

25:29.403 --> 25:31.822
This isn't your business.
It doesn't concern you.

25:31.822 --> 25:33.699
You testified
against me, Bill.

25:33.699 --> 25:36.576
Now I see you're taking
a stroll down the boardwalk

25:36.576 --> 25:38.496
with my coconspirator.

25:38.496 --> 25:41.165
No, no, no. You and me
are not the same.

25:41.165 --> 25:43.876
Actions speak volumes,
Miss Foster.

25:43.876 --> 25:45.711
Keep a close eye
on her, Bill.

25:45.711 --> 25:48.255
Make sure she doesn't
get away from you again.

25:48.255 --> 25:50.466
[♪♪♪]

25:53.344 --> 25:54.636
[SIGHS HEAVILY]

25:54.636 --> 25:56.722
Ah...

25:58.556 --> 25:59.933
[DOOR OPENS]

25:59.933 --> 26:01.394
Doc?

26:01.394 --> 26:03.145
What happened, Jesse?

26:03.145 --> 26:04.313
Ah, a board bucked

26:04.313 --> 26:05.939
going through
the saw at the mill.

26:05.939 --> 26:07.607
Got a sliver
I can't get rid of.

26:07.607 --> 26:08.692
Let's take a look.

26:08.692 --> 26:11.195
Oh, finally.

26:11.195 --> 26:13.406
[♪♪♪]

26:15.241 --> 26:17.451
Oh, do you mind if Robert
stays in the room?

26:17.451 --> 26:19.328
It's part of
his class project.

26:19.328 --> 26:21.247
Sure. Yeah.

26:24.582 --> 26:26.584
CARSON:
Yeah.

26:29.587 --> 26:31.048
Oh, yeah. It's wedged

26:31.048 --> 26:32.841
in there pretty deep.
JESSE: Yep.

26:32.841 --> 26:35.969
This...is what we use
to sterilize the area,

26:35.969 --> 26:38.596
so the wound
doesn't get infected.

26:38.596 --> 26:40.640
Could you grab me
the forceps, please?

26:44.061 --> 26:45.645
Forceps.

26:46.480 --> 26:48.107
[CLICKS TONGUE]
Okay.

26:48.107 --> 26:50.234
This might hurt
a little bit, Jesse.

26:50.234 --> 26:51.235
Okay.

26:51.235 --> 26:52.319
[SUCKS BREATH IN]

26:55.448 --> 26:57.074
Uh...

26:57.074 --> 26:59.326
Wait. Are you--?

26:59.326 --> 27:00.869
[GRUNTS]
FAITH: Oh!

27:05.583 --> 27:07.042
[CHUCKLES]

27:09.587 --> 27:11.755
Now, you must see
our beautiful church.

27:11.755 --> 27:13.507
It is so charming.
It's over there.

27:13.507 --> 27:14.967
Getting to know
Hope Valley?

27:14.967 --> 27:16.427
Oh! Yes.

27:16.427 --> 27:19.012
These ladies have been
giving me the grand tour.

27:19.012 --> 27:20.222
Where are you headed?

27:20.222 --> 27:22.057
I'm checking on
some of my students.

27:22.057 --> 27:23.683
Ah. Well,
I'll walk with you.

27:23.683 --> 27:25.769
We haven't shown you
the railway depot yet.

27:25.769 --> 27:27.605
It is brand new.
Mm-hmm.

27:27.605 --> 27:29.356
I saw it on the way in.

27:29.356 --> 27:30.899
Quaint.

27:30.899 --> 27:32.610
Thank you very much
for the tour.

27:32.610 --> 27:34.987
Oh, our pleasure.
You have a lovely day.

27:34.987 --> 27:37.781
If there's anything you need,
you know where to find us.

27:37.781 --> 27:40.242
[ALL CHUCKLING]

27:40.242 --> 27:44.455
Well, people here are quite
enthusiastic about this town.

27:44.455 --> 27:47.333
Because it truly is
such a special place.

27:47.333 --> 27:49.460
Did you meet some
of the merchants yet?

27:49.460 --> 27:51.629
I did.
They are quite friendly.

27:51.629 --> 27:53.213
I stopped by the saloon,
as well.

27:53.213 --> 27:55.090
It's a little rough
around the edges,

27:55.090 --> 27:56.383
but it serves
its purpose,

27:56.383 --> 27:59.094
and some delicious
libations as well.

27:59.094 --> 28:00.596
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

28:00.596 --> 28:02.431
I don't know
much about investments,

28:02.431 --> 28:03.681
but I do know people,

28:03.681 --> 28:06.059
and you won't find
any better than here.

28:06.059 --> 28:07.645
Mm.

28:08.312 --> 28:10.272
Elizabeth...

28:10.272 --> 28:12.274
Are you trying
to turn our social visit

28:12.274 --> 28:13.150
into a business one?

28:13.150 --> 28:14.818
[♪♪♪]

28:14.818 --> 28:16.529
I just think it's important

28:16.529 --> 28:18.238
that you to get
to know the town.

28:18.238 --> 28:19.448
Understood.

28:19.448 --> 28:21.408
But my business day is done.

28:22.993 --> 28:24.786
Let's talk about you.

28:24.786 --> 28:26.413
Oh! Well...

28:26.413 --> 28:28.541
[GROANS]

28:28.541 --> 28:30.750
[♪♪♪]

28:35.005 --> 28:36.714
What happened?

28:36.714 --> 28:39.134
You just got a little woozy.

28:39.134 --> 28:40.886
Oh, right.

28:40.886 --> 28:43.055
Here,
drink this apple juice.

28:43.055 --> 28:44.973
Does it have to be apple?

28:44.973 --> 28:47.560
Drink.
It's good for you.

28:51.230 --> 28:52.356
I'm sorry.

28:52.356 --> 28:54.149
Ah, happens
to the best of us.

28:54.149 --> 28:55.526
When I was in med school,

28:55.526 --> 28:57.653
we'd take bets
who would pass out first

28:57.653 --> 28:59.279
during hospital rounds.

28:59.279 --> 29:01.990
My first few weeks there,
I was even odds.

29:01.990 --> 29:02.866
[LAUGHS]

29:02.866 --> 29:04.159
You?
CARSON: Yeah.

29:04.159 --> 29:05.536
When I was your age,

29:05.536 --> 29:08.497
just the sight of blood
would make me woozy.

29:08.497 --> 29:10.165
And you still became a doctor?

29:10.165 --> 29:12.501
Yeah, and so could you,
if you really want it,

29:12.501 --> 29:14.336
if you don't give up.

29:14.336 --> 29:15.504
Thanks.

29:15.504 --> 29:16.963
So, now...

29:16.963 --> 29:18.131
you feeling better?

29:18.131 --> 29:19.758
Yeah.
Good.

29:19.758 --> 29:21.552
That'll be $2.

29:21.552 --> 29:23.554
What?

29:23.554 --> 29:25.431
For my medical services.

29:25.431 --> 29:27.558
Uh...
I don't have any money.

29:27.558 --> 29:30.894
Ooh. What do
you think, Doctor?

29:30.894 --> 29:33.146
Should we call the Sheriff?
Have him arrested?

29:33.146 --> 29:34.732
CARSON:
I think...

29:34.732 --> 29:37.859
we should do this one
free of charge.

29:37.859 --> 29:39.528
Don't you think?

29:39.528 --> 29:40.946
[SIGHS]

29:40.946 --> 29:43.031
Absolutely.

29:43.031 --> 29:44.658
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

29:47.119 --> 29:50.330
Why did you let Gowen
come back to Hope Valley?

29:50.330 --> 29:52.416
I didn't have much say
in the matter.

29:52.416 --> 29:54.793
Doesn't sound like
the Bill Avery I remember.

29:54.793 --> 29:57.421
Seemed to me you were used
to getting your own way.

29:57.421 --> 29:58.547
Well, not this time.

29:58.547 --> 30:00.507
Abigail believes
people can change.

30:00.507 --> 30:02.301
Hmm. And you don't?

30:02.301 --> 30:04.637
I suppose you'll tell me
you're a new person.

30:04.637 --> 30:07.180
It sounds like, if I did,
you wouldn't believe me.

30:07.180 --> 30:10.100
You're probably right.
And you'd be wrong.

30:10.100 --> 30:12.311
[♪♪♪]

30:12.311 --> 30:15.230
Maybe Baxter's
out for the day.

30:15.230 --> 30:17.983
Listen, all I want
is a normal life again,

30:17.983 --> 30:20.360
with good people,
in a good town.

30:20.360 --> 30:23.989
Then for your sake,
I hope you find that.

30:27.867 --> 30:29.536
There he is.

30:33.415 --> 30:35.083
You recognize him?

30:35.083 --> 30:36.669
[SIGHS]
Hmm.

30:39.087 --> 30:41.131
I think
I might need a closer look.

30:41.131 --> 30:42.508
Hey, hey--

30:42.508 --> 30:44.718
[♪♪♪]

30:46.219 --> 30:47.887
Hello.

30:49.097 --> 30:51.099
You're new around here,
aren't you?

30:51.099 --> 30:52.976
Why, yes, I am.

30:52.976 --> 30:55.187
I know everybody here
in Hope Valley

30:55.187 --> 30:57.481
and I don't recognize you.

30:57.481 --> 31:00.275
Maybe we can remedy that.

31:00.275 --> 31:04.279
No. I don't sit with a man
who doesn't stand for a lady.

31:05.947 --> 31:08.325
BAXTER:
Pardon me, ma'am.

31:09.535 --> 31:11.328
May I?

31:11.328 --> 31:13.288
Please.

31:13.288 --> 31:14.998
Thank you.

31:14.998 --> 31:17.209
[♪♪♪]

31:22.088 --> 31:23.382
Oh, thank you.

31:25.091 --> 31:27.469
I remember you always
wanted to be a teacher

31:27.469 --> 31:28.887
and a writer.

31:28.887 --> 31:31.973
So far, I've only
accomplished the one.

31:31.973 --> 31:34.017
Well, don't give up.

31:34.017 --> 31:36.228
I recall you were
quite good.

31:36.228 --> 31:38.647
Thanks.

31:38.647 --> 31:41.483
It is quite
something to see...

31:41.483 --> 31:43.151
the woman that
you've grown into.

31:43.151 --> 31:44.528
Oh.

31:44.528 --> 31:46.572
I hear your wedding
was quite the affair.

31:46.572 --> 31:49.408
Oh, ho! So I guess
Florence and Molly

31:49.408 --> 31:51.243
did more than just
show you the sights.

31:51.243 --> 31:53.995
Oh, those two ladies
can spin a tale.
Sorry.

31:53.995 --> 31:56.289
Oh, no, it was
quite entertaining.

31:56.289 --> 31:58.250
I don't know what's
more extraordinary,

31:58.250 --> 32:01.420
the hero Mountie,
or your father coming around.

32:01.420 --> 32:02.921
[LAUGHS]

32:02.921 --> 32:04.964
I'd say
by the blushing bride,

32:04.964 --> 32:06.550
it's the Mountie.

32:06.550 --> 32:09.052
And you would be right.
[CHUCKLES]

32:09.052 --> 32:12.264
But enough about me,
how have you been?

32:12.264 --> 32:15.183
Well, most of my time is spent
in business meetings

32:15.183 --> 32:17.895
or on the road, traveling to
other business meetings.

32:17.895 --> 32:19.062
How's Duncan?

32:19.062 --> 32:21.440
I'm sure he's fine.

32:21.440 --> 32:23.817
Well, that doesn't
sound very convincing.

32:25.318 --> 32:28.864
My son and I haven't spoken
in a number of years.

32:28.864 --> 32:30.323
[♪♪♪]

32:30.323 --> 32:33.452
I'm so sorry.
I-I had no idea.

32:34.453 --> 32:36.580
May I ask what happened?

32:36.580 --> 32:39.833
It's not important.

32:39.833 --> 32:41.501
Well, I better go.

32:41.501 --> 32:43.879
I need to rest up,
I have a big day tomorrow.

32:43.879 --> 32:46.005
I hope I didn't say
anything wrong.

32:46.005 --> 32:47.883
No, darling.

32:47.883 --> 32:49.593
I'm just
feeling a little tired.

32:50.552 --> 32:52.011
And I think
it might be time

32:52.011 --> 32:54.556
to have another gander
around the saloon.

32:56.141 --> 32:58.351
[♪♪♪]

33:12.783 --> 33:13.909
Hello?

33:13.909 --> 33:15.368
OPAL:
Hello!

33:15.368 --> 33:17.370
[GASPS]

33:20.666 --> 33:23.084
May I help you?

33:23.084 --> 33:25.587
[LAUGHS]

33:25.587 --> 33:27.297
Opal.

33:28.632 --> 33:31.760
Oh, maybe later.

33:31.760 --> 33:33.679
[LAUGHS]

33:33.679 --> 33:36.515
[AJ LAUGHING]
[BAXTER SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

33:36.515 --> 33:38.475
BAXTER: ...and then I fired him.
AJ: Oh!

33:38.475 --> 33:41.561
Oh...well.

33:41.561 --> 33:44.063
This has been delightful.

33:44.063 --> 33:46.024
Allow me.

33:51.822 --> 33:53.281
Mademoiselle...

33:53.281 --> 33:54.282
Oh...

33:54.282 --> 33:56.535
[♪♪♪]

34:21.977 --> 34:24.187
[♪♪♪]

34:30.652 --> 34:32.278
Well?

34:32.278 --> 34:35.114
Oh, I recognized him right
when he walked in the door.

34:35.114 --> 34:36.491
Why did you sit at his table?

34:36.491 --> 34:39.703
I wanted to see
the look on your face.

34:41.747 --> 34:43.957
Tell me about Baxter.

34:46.835 --> 34:49.504
AJ:
A few months ago,
I passed through

34:49.504 --> 34:52.090
this small Texas town
called Caneridge,

34:52.090 --> 34:54.175
and Baxter ran the bank.

34:54.175 --> 34:55.928
Tell her what kind
of town it is.

34:55.928 --> 34:58.096
Well, there was
lots of gambling, and--

34:58.096 --> 35:00.557
It wasn't a family town,
if you know what I mean.

35:00.557 --> 35:01.767
Nothing like Hope Valley.

35:01.767 --> 35:03.602
Where the sheriff
and the mayor

35:03.602 --> 35:05.270
are happy
to look the other way.

35:05.270 --> 35:06.939
Were they being paid off?

35:06.939 --> 35:09.190
I can't say for sure,
but it looked like

35:09.190 --> 35:10.734
he controlled the whole town.

35:10.734 --> 35:12.069
[EXHALES HEAVILY]

35:12.069 --> 35:14.279
We need to more information
on Mr. Baxter.

35:14.279 --> 35:16.531
I have a friend
that's a Texas Ranger.

35:16.531 --> 35:19.200
I'm gonna wire him to make sure
her story checks out.

35:19.200 --> 35:20.452
[SIGHS]

35:20.452 --> 35:22.579
[♪♪♪]

35:27.375 --> 35:29.127
All right, everyone.

35:29.127 --> 35:32.213
Today, we're going to discuss
what we learned about business.

35:32.213 --> 35:33.548
Emily?

35:33.548 --> 35:35.675
I learned there are
rules to being creative.

35:35.675 --> 35:39.220
[IMITATING ROSEMARY]
It's best that you know them
before you break them.

35:39.220 --> 35:42.808
[LAUGHS]
Okay. Excellent point.

35:42.808 --> 35:44.101
Yes, Opal?

35:44.101 --> 35:45.769
I like eggs.

35:46.728 --> 35:48.187
Wonderful, sweetheart.

35:48.187 --> 35:49.773
Robert?

35:49.773 --> 35:52.776
I learned that doctors don't
always make a lot of money.

35:52.776 --> 35:54.193
Sometimes,
they don't charge

35:54.193 --> 35:55.946
'cause it's
the right thing to do.

35:55.946 --> 35:57.405
Well, if you're lucky enough

35:57.405 --> 35:59.908
to have a doctor
like Carson Shepherd.

36:00.826 --> 36:02.953
Has anyone seen Cody?

36:06.081 --> 36:07.791
Uh, everyone,

36:07.791 --> 36:11.544
please open up your readers
and start reading from page 10.

36:14.213 --> 36:16.758
So look who I found at
the sawmill this morning.

36:16.758 --> 36:19.469
Cody, you know that our
project was only for one day.

36:19.469 --> 36:20.971
Why did you go there?

36:20.971 --> 36:23.598
So that I could spend
another day with Mr. Coulter.

36:25.017 --> 36:27.393
Is there a reason
why you wanted to do that?

36:27.393 --> 36:30.063
I don't know. It was fun
spending time with him.

36:30.063 --> 36:31.857
Oh, that's nice.

36:31.857 --> 36:33.232
Well, Cody,

36:33.232 --> 36:35.610
Mr. Coulter has work,
and you have school,

36:35.610 --> 36:37.737
so why don't you take a seat
and open your reader?

36:37.737 --> 36:39.405
Okay. Bye, Mr. Coulter.

36:39.405 --> 36:41.074
Bye, Cody.

36:42.784 --> 36:44.661
He stayed late yesterday
so I could

36:44.661 --> 36:46.079
teach him to sign paychecks.

36:46.079 --> 36:48.081
I don't know. His friends

36:48.081 --> 36:51.126
were playing outside.
He didn't care.

36:51.126 --> 36:54.629
I suspect this is about more
than just signing checks.

36:54.629 --> 36:56.214
Yeah, I suspect so.

36:56.214 --> 36:57.757
But that's all right,
I get it.

36:57.757 --> 36:59.843
My father was
a traveling salesman.

36:59.843 --> 37:02.303
He was home maybe
three times a month.

37:02.303 --> 37:04.097
He sold carpet-sweepers.
Very boring.

37:04.097 --> 37:05.765
I had to pretend
to be interested,

37:05.765 --> 37:07.809
just so I could spend
more time with him.

37:07.809 --> 37:10.145
[LAUGHS]
Well, thanks for
bringing him back.

37:10.145 --> 37:12.856
Yeah, it's okay. No problem.
Bye, Elizabeth.

37:12.856 --> 37:14.357
Bye.

37:14.357 --> 37:16.526
[♪♪♪]

37:17.861 --> 37:19.278
[SIGHS]

37:20.989 --> 37:23.366
Greta!
How are you doing?

37:23.366 --> 37:25.577
Elizabeth.
Well, I spent the morning

37:25.577 --> 37:27.204
reviewing the bank's books.

37:27.204 --> 37:28.955
What did you find?

37:28.955 --> 37:31.290
Well, numbers don't lie,
darling, and...

37:31.290 --> 37:32.375
it's not pretty.

37:32.375 --> 37:33.793
Mr. Jenkins...

37:33.793 --> 37:36.629
he's made
some very bad loans.

37:36.629 --> 37:38.798
[GROANS]
But there
are opportunities

37:38.798 --> 37:40.633
for growth
here in Hope Valley.

37:40.633 --> 37:42.886
And have you made a decision?

37:42.886 --> 37:44.054
Not yet.

37:44.054 --> 37:45.805
I still have a few books
to review.

37:45.805 --> 37:46.932
I'm pretty thorough.

37:46.932 --> 37:48.058
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

37:48.058 --> 37:50.268
[♪♪♪]

37:51.937 --> 37:55.440
You know, Greta, I can't help
thinking about you and Duncan.

37:55.440 --> 37:58.860
You two used
to be so close.

37:59.903 --> 38:01.988
Well...ahem.

38:01.988 --> 38:03.406
Things change.

38:03.406 --> 38:05.200
But between a mother and son?

38:05.200 --> 38:07.410
Things shouldn't change
like that.

38:07.410 --> 38:09.204
[INHALES DEEPLY]

38:09.204 --> 38:11.581
[SIGHS]
I really must go.

38:14.417 --> 38:16.544
[SIGHS]

38:23.969 --> 38:26.554
How's your reunion
going with Mrs. Preston?

38:26.554 --> 38:28.098
Well, it was going well,

38:28.098 --> 38:31.017
until I found out she hasn't
spoken to her son in years.

38:31.017 --> 38:33.519
Oh. I'm sorry to
hear that.

38:33.519 --> 38:35.563
Me too.
When we were young,

38:35.563 --> 38:37.899
Duncan was one
of my best friends.

38:37.899 --> 38:40.110
I just wish there was
something I could do.

38:40.110 --> 38:41.527
I wonder what happened.

38:41.527 --> 38:42.821
I'm not sure.

38:42.821 --> 38:44.697
I know their family
was never the same

38:44.697 --> 38:46.116
after Duncan's
father died.

38:46.116 --> 38:47.575
It never is.

38:47.575 --> 38:49.368
[♪♪♪]

38:49.368 --> 38:50.829
You know, there's
another boy

38:50.829 --> 38:52.956
I was hoping
to talk to you about.

38:52.956 --> 38:54.874
Cody.

38:54.874 --> 38:57.043
He didn't show up
for school this morning.

38:57.043 --> 38:58.837
Instead, he went
back to Lee's mill.

38:58.837 --> 39:00.463
Lee brought him back
to school,

39:00.463 --> 39:01.881
but it was clear

39:01.881 --> 39:04.634
that Cody wanted to spend
more time with him.

39:04.634 --> 39:06.094
I think
Cody's at an age

39:06.094 --> 39:08.721
where he needs
a man in his life.

39:10.598 --> 39:12.725
[DOOR OPENS]

39:17.605 --> 39:19.899
I'll leave you two alone.

39:22.902 --> 39:24.362
How are you doing, Cody?

39:24.362 --> 39:26.031
I'm okay.

39:26.031 --> 39:28.658
I hear you didn't
go to school this morning.

39:28.658 --> 39:31.119
I was learning
a lot at the mill.

39:31.119 --> 39:32.662
I bet you were,

39:32.662 --> 39:34.706
but you do know
you have to go to school.

39:34.706 --> 39:36.499
I know.

39:36.499 --> 39:39.502
Cody...I feel terrible
that I've been

39:39.502 --> 39:42.297
spending all this time
on the bank stuff.

39:42.297 --> 39:43.589
I understand.

39:43.589 --> 39:44.924
It's important stuff.

39:44.924 --> 39:48.053
It is, but not
more important than you.

39:49.221 --> 39:50.847
I love you, Cody.

39:50.847 --> 39:52.265
I love you too, Mom.

39:53.474 --> 39:54.851
Hey, how about this weekend,

39:54.851 --> 39:56.978
you and I go to your favorite
fishing spot?

39:56.978 --> 39:58.855
Sure.

39:58.855 --> 40:00.815
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

40:00.815 --> 40:02.359
I'll get it.

40:07.488 --> 40:09.574
Hi, Mr. Coulter!

40:09.574 --> 40:11.368
Hey, Cody.
Hi, Abigail.

40:11.368 --> 40:12.869
Lee.
I was hoping that

40:12.869 --> 40:14.246
Cody could help me today.

40:14.246 --> 40:15.538
What's that?

40:15.538 --> 40:17.749
I was thinking
we could play some catch.

40:17.749 --> 40:18.958
Really?

40:18.958 --> 40:20.210
Well, the mill has a team,

40:20.210 --> 40:22.087
and we have
this big game next month,

40:22.087 --> 40:24.672
and, uh, well, the truth is,
I'm a little rusty,

40:24.672 --> 40:26.841
but I heard you're fantastic.

40:26.841 --> 40:28.593
I was thinking you could
show me a few things.

40:28.593 --> 40:30.053
Could I ever!

40:30.053 --> 40:32.264
I mean...may I?

40:32.264 --> 40:34.391
Yes, you may.

40:35.725 --> 40:37.102
[WHISPERS]
Thank you.

40:37.102 --> 40:38.477
[WHISPERS]
You're welcome.

40:38.477 --> 40:40.730
Come on, young man. Let's go!

40:40.730 --> 40:42.941
[♪♪♪]

40:46.986 --> 40:51.490
I can almost touch your face
when I throw it with my hand.

40:51.490 --> 40:53.410
There we go. Ready? Up!

40:53.410 --> 40:54.869
[IMITATES AN AIRPLANE]

40:54.869 --> 40:56.162
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

40:57.080 --> 40:58.915
Bill.

40:58.915 --> 41:00.125
What did you find out?

41:00.125 --> 41:02.210
Everything AJ said
checks out.

41:02.210 --> 41:04.337
Baxter has a history
of taking small towns

41:04.337 --> 41:06.672
and turning them into
something we don't want.

41:06.672 --> 41:08.216
We need to warn Jenkins.

41:08.216 --> 41:10.427
[♪♪♪]

41:14.306 --> 41:16.057
Oh, no.

41:16.057 --> 41:17.767
Mr. Jenkins.

41:17.767 --> 41:19.811
I have wonderful news,
Mayor Stanton.

41:19.811 --> 41:21.229
Mr. Baxter has agreed

41:21.229 --> 41:23.148
to take a majority share
in the bank.

41:23.148 --> 41:25.900
We're gonna do great
things with this town.

41:25.900 --> 41:28.111
[♪♪♪]

41:30.696 --> 41:32.907
[♪♪♪]
